{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512983"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:04:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:04:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11987"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11987"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.29,0.44,0.16,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51501"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4577"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11987"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36800"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1132"},{"type":"tags","id":"1309"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"6146"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6887"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43285"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51501"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with right ankle pain. She was playing netball this afternoon when she jumped for a high ball and landed awkwardly on her right ankle, feeling it roll inward. The onset of pain and swelling was immediate. She could not bear weight and needed assistance to leave the court. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. She is able to walk from waiting room to consult area without assistance, though demonstrates obvious pain on ambulation. Her vital signs are within normal limits. There is significant swelling in the right ankle, especially on the lateral aspect, and the anterolateral aspect of the foot. Bruising is beginning to show over the anterior aspect of the foot. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most suggestive of the need to perform a plain X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Significant swelling of the ankle","Inability to bear weight at the time of injury","Pain or tenderness at the base of the 5th metatarsal","Inability to plantarflex the right foot passively or actively","Pain or tenderness in the anterolateral aspect of the foot"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question assesses knowledge of the Ottawa ankle rules, a validated set of criteria used to determine the need for plain radiographs in patients presenting with acute ankle and midfoot injuries. The Ottawa ankle rules have a sensitivity of 90-100% for clinically significant ankle and midfoot fractures, making them a useful tool to rule out significant injury and avoid unnecessary imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the Ottawa ankle rules, an ankle X-ray is required if there is:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPain or tenderness along the distal 6 cm of the posterior edge of either malleolus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInability to bear weight both immediately after the injury and in the Emergency Department\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA foot X-ray is required if there is:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPain or tenderness at the base of the 5th metatarsal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPain or tenderness at the navicular bone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInability to bear weight both immediately after the injury and for four steps during initial assessment in the Emergency Department\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain or tenderness at the base of the 5th metatarsal\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the specific criteria in the Ottawa ankle rules indicating the need for a foot X-ray. This is the correct answer as it directly corresponds to one of the rule\u0027s criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESignificant swelling of the ankle\u003C/strong\u003E, while a common finding in ankle injuries, is not a specific criterion in the Ottawa ankle rules. However, if swelling is severe enough to prevent accurate palpation of the malleoli, clinical judgment should take precedence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInability to bear weight at the time of injury\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not sufficient according to the rules. The patient must be unable to bear weight both immediately after the injury AND at the time of assessment in the Emergency Department, however in this case the patient can bear weight at the time of assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInability to plantarflex the right foot\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of the Ottawa ankle rules. While it may indicate a significant injury, it is not a specific criterion for X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain or tenderness in the anterolateral aspect of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E is not a specific criterion in the Ottawa ankle rules, unless it corresponds to the base of the 5th metatarsal or the navicular bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while the Ottawa ankle rules are highly sensitive, clinical judgment should always be used, especially in cases where the patient is uncooperative, intoxicated, has other distracting injuries, or has diminished sensation in the legs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Ottawa ankle rules are a validated clinical decision-making tool for determining the need for X-rays in acute ankle and midfoot injuries.","Pain or tenderness at the base of the 5th metatarsal is one of the criteria in the Ottawa ankle rules indicating the need for an X-ray."],"references":["Stiell IG, Greenberg GH, McKnight RD, Nair RC, McDowell I, Worthington JR. A study to develop clinical decision rules for the use of radiography in acute ankle injuries. Ann Emerg Med. 1992 Apr;21(4):384-90. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1554175/","Stiell IG, McKnight RD, Greenberg GH, McDowell I, Nair RC, Wells GA, et al. Implementation of the Ottawa ankle rules. JAMA. 1994 Mar 16;271(11):827-32. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/367534"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36800"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11987"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36800"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-26T12:11:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-26T12:12:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4577"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51501"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1132"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"X-ray - skull","synonyms":["Skull XR","Skull X-ray"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-07-24T01:28:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T09:31:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"4"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1309"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Ankle pain","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-08-22T01:00:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:18:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4974"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Musculoskeletal Presentations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T